# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: amoebozoa
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:amoebozoa/abdominal-pain] Common causes of pain in the abdomen include gastroenteritis and irritable bowel syndrome.
[src:amoebozoa/abdominal-pain] About 15% of people have a more serious underlying condition such as appendicitis, leaking or ruptured abdominal aortic aneurysm, diverticulitis, or ectopic pregnancy.
[src:amoebozoa/abdominal-pain] In a third of cases, the exact cause is unclear.
[src:amoebozoa/abdominal-pain] The onset of abdominal pain can be abrupt, quick, or gradual.
[src:amoebozoa/abdominal-pain] Sudden onset pain happens nearly instantaneously.
[src:amoebozoa/abdominal-pain] Rapidly onset pain starts mild and gets worse over the next few minutes.
[src:amoebozoa/abdominal-pain] Pain that gradually intensifies only after several hours or even days has passed is referred to as gradual onset pain.
[src:amoebozoa/abdominal-pain] One can describe abdominal pain as either continuous or sporadic and as cramping, dull, or aching.
[src:amoebozoa/abdominal-pain] The characteristic of cramping abdominal pain is that it comes in brief waves, builds to a peak, and then abruptly stops for a period during which there is no more pain.
[src:amoebozoa/abdominal-pain] The pain flares up and off periodically.
[src:amoebozoa/abdominal-pain] The most common cause of persistent dull or aching abdominal pain is edema or distention of the wall of a hollow viscus.
[src:amoebozoa/abdominal-pain] A dull or aching pain may also be felt due to a stretch in the liver and spleen capsules.
[src:amoebozoa/abdominal-pain] The most frequent reasons for abdominal pain are gastroenteritis (13%), irritable bowel syndrome (8%), urinary tract problems (5%), inflammation of the stomach (5%) and constipation (5%).
[src:amoebozoa/abdominal-pain] In about 30% of cases, the cause is not determined.
[src:amoebozoa/abdominal-pain] About 10% of cases have a more serious cause including gallbladder (gallstones or biliary dyskinesia) or pancreas problems (4%), diverticulitis (3%), appendicitis (2%) and cancer (1%).
[src:amoebozoa/abdominal-pain] More common in those who are older, ischemic colitis, mesenteric ischemia, and abdominal aortic aneurysms are other serious causes.
[src:amoebozoa/abdominal-pain] Acute abdomen is a condition where there is a sudden onset of severe abdominal pain requiring immediate recognition and management of the underlying cause.
[src:amoebozoa/abdominal-pain] The underlying cause may involve infection, inflammation, vascular occlusion or bowel obstruction.
[src:amoebozoa/abdominal-pain] The pain may elicit nausea and vomiting, abdominal distention, fever and signs of shock.
[src:amoebozoa/abdominal-pain] A common condition associated with acute abdominal pain is appendicitis.
[src:amoebozoa/abdominal-pain] The location of abdominal pain can provide information about what may be causing the pain.
[src:amoebozoa/abdominal-pain] The abdomen can be divided into four regions called quadrants.
[src:amoebozoa/abdominal-pain] Abdominal pain can be referred to as visceral pain or peritoneal pain.
[src:amoebozoa/abdominal-pain] The contents of the abdomen can be divided into the foregut, midgut, and hindgut.
[src:amoebozoa/abdominal-pain] The foregut contains the pharynx, lower respiratory tract, portions of the esophagus, stomach, portions of the duodenum (proximal), liver, biliary tract (including the gallbladder and bile ducts), and the pancreas.
[src:amoebozoa/abdominal-pain] The midgut contains portions of the duodenum (distal), cecum, appendix, ascending colon, and first half of the transverse colon.
[src:amoebozoa/abdominal-pain] The hindgut contains the distal half of the transverse colon, descending colon, sigmoid colon, rectum, and superior anal canal.
[src:amoebozoa/abdominal-pain] Each subsection of the gut has an associated visceral afferent nerve that transmits sensory information from the viscera to the spinal cord.
[src:amoebozoa/abdominal-pain] The visceral sensory information from the gut traveling to the spinal cord, termed the visceral afferent, is non-specific and overlaps with the somatic afferent nerves, which are very specific.
[src:amoebozoa/abdominal-pain] A thorough patient history and physical examination is used to better understand the underlying cause of abdominal pain.
[src:amoebozoa/abdominal-pain] After gathering a thorough history, one should perform a physical exam in order to identify important physical signs that might clarify the diagnosis, including a cardiovascular exam, lung exam, thorough abdominal exam, and for females, a genitourinary exam.
[src:amoebozoa/abdominal-pain] If diagnosis remains unclear after history, examination, and basic investigations as above, then more advanced investigations may reveal a diagnosis.
[src:amoebozoa/abdominal-pain] The management of abdominal pain depends on many factors, including the etiology of the pain.
[src:amoebozoa/abdominal-pain] Some behavioural changes implemented to prevent pain include: resting after a meal, chewing food completely and slowly, and avoiding stressful and high excitement situations after a meal.
[src:amoebozoa/abdominal-pain] Such at home strategies may reduce the need to seek professional assistance via prevention of future abdominal pain.
[src:amoebozoa/abdominal-pain] In the emergency department, a person presenting with abdominal pain may initially require IV fluids due to decreased intake secondary to abdominal pain and possible emesis or vomiting.
[src:amoebozoa/abdominal-pain] Treatment for abdominal pain includes analgesia, such as non-opioid (ketorolac) and opioid medications (morphine, fentanyl).
[src:amoebozoa/abdominal-pain] Choice of analgesia is dependent on the cause of the pain, as ketorolac can worsen some intra-abdominal processes.
[src:amoebozoa/abdominal-pain] Patients presenting to the emergency department with abdominal pain may receive a "GI cocktail" that includes an antacid (examples include omeprazole, famotidine, magnesium hydroxide, and calcium carbonate) and lidocaine.
[src:amoebozoa/abdominal-pain] After addressing pain, there may be a role for antimicrobial treatment in some cases of abdominal pain.
[src:amoebozoa/abdominal-pain] Butylscopolamine (Buscopan) is used to treat cramping abdominal pain with some success.
[src:amoebozoa/abdominal-pain] Surgical management for causes of abdominal pain includes but is not limited to cholecystectomy, appendectomy, and exploratory laparotomy.
[src:amoebozoa/abdominal-pain] Below is a brief overview of abdominal pain emergencies.
[src:amoebozoa/abdominal-pain] One well-known aspect of primary health care is its low prevalence of potentially dangerous abdominal pain causes.
[src:amoebozoa/abdominal-pain] Patients with abdominal pain have a higher percentage of unexplained complaints (category "no diagnosis") than patients with other symptoms (such as dyspnea or chest pain).
[src:amoebozoa/abdominal-pain] Most people who suffer from stomach pain have a benign issue, like dyspepsia.
[src:amoebozoa/abdominal-pain] In general, it is discovered that 20% to 25% of patients with abdominal pain have a serious condition that necessitates admission to an acute care hospital.
[src:amoebozoa/abdominal-pain] Abdominal pain is the reason about 3% of adults see their family physician.
[src:amoebozoa/abdominal-pain] Rates of emergency department (ED) visits in the United States for abdominal pain increased 18% from 2006 through to 2011.
[src:amoebozoa/abdominal-pain] This was the largest increase out of 20 common conditions seen in the ED.
[src:amoebozoa/abdominal-pain] The rate of ED use for nausea and vomiting also increased 18%.
[src:amoebozoa/abdominal-pain] More time and resources are used on older patients with abdominal pain than on any other patient presentation in the emergency department (ED).
[src:amoebozoa/abdominal-pain] Compared to younger patients with the same complaint, their length of stay is 20% longer, they need to be admitted almost half the time, and they need surgery 1/3 of the time.
[src:amoebozoa/abdominal-pain] Age does not reduce the total number of T cells, but it does reduce their functionality.
[src:amoebozoa/abdominal-pain] The elderly person's ability to fight infection is weakened as a result.
[src:amoebozoa/abdominal-pain] Additionally, they have changed the strength and integrity of their skin and mucous membranes, which are physical barriers to infection.
[src:amoebozoa/abdominal-pain] It is well known that older patients experience altered pain perception.
[src:amoebozoa/abdominal-pain] The challenge of obtaining a sufficient history from an elderly patient can be attributed to multiple factors.
[src:amoebozoa/abdominal-pain] Reduced memory or hearing could make the issue worse.
[src:amoebozoa/abdominal-pain] It is common to encounter stoicism combined with a fear of losing one's independence if a serious condition is discovered.
[src:amoebozoa/abdominal-pain] Changes in mental status, whether acute or chronic, are common.
[src:amoebozoa/abdominal-pain] Unique clinical challenges arise when pregnant women experience abdominal pain.
[src:amoebozoa/abdominal-pain] First off, there are many possible causes of abdominal pain during pregnancy.
[src:amoebozoa/abdominal-pain] These include intraabdominal diseases that arise incidentally during pregnancy as well as obstetric or gynecologic disorders associated with pregnancy.
[src:amoebozoa/abdominal-pain] Secondly, pregnancy modifies the natural history and clinical manifestation of numerous abdominal disorders.
[src:amoebozoa/abdominal-pain] Third, pregnancy modifies and limits the diagnostic assessment.
[src:amoebozoa/abdominal-pain] For instance, concerns about fetal safety during pregnancy are raised by invasive exams and radiologic testing.
[src:amoebozoa/abdominal-pain] Fourth, while receiving therapy during pregnancy, the mother's and the fetus' interests need to be taken into account.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba-keratitis] Infection of the cornea by *Acanthamoeba* is difficult to treat with conventional medications, and AK may cause permanent visual impairment or blindness, due to damage to the cornea or through damage to other structures important to vision.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba-keratitis] Recently, AK has been recognized as an orphan disease and a funded project, Orphan Drug for Acanthamoeba Keratitis (ODAK), has tested the effects of a diverse range drugs and biocides on AK.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba-keratitis] In the United States, *Acanthamoeba* keratitis is nearly always associated with soft contact lens use.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba-keratitis] *Acanthamoeba* spp. is most commonly introduced to the eye by contact lenses that have been exposed to the organism through the use of contaminated lens solution, using homemade saline-based solution or tap water, or from wearing contact lenses while bathing or swimming.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba-keratitis] However, it may also be introduced to the eye by exposure to soil or vegetation, or by trauma.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba-keratitis] In fact, the first case of *Acanthamoeba* keratitis described was due to ocular trauma.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba-keratitis] Once on the contact lens, *Acanthamoeba* is able to survive in the space between the contact lens and the surface of the eye.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba-keratitis] Soft contact lenses are more adherent to the corneal surface than hard lenses, which allows the *Acanthamoeba* organism to bind to mannosylated glycoproteins on the corneal surface.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba-keratitis] Expression of these proteins on the corneal surface is increased by contact lens use.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba-keratitis] This increase in glycoprotein content, along with microtrauma to the corneal epithelial surface due to contact lens use increases the risk for infection.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba-keratitis] Once the organism has gained access to the surface of the eye, it is able to invade through the epithelium and Bowman's layer.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba-keratitis] In some cases, the infection can then group around corneal nerves, producing radial deposits (radial keratoneuritis), and causing extreme pain.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba-keratitis] These are features also seen in viral and bacterial keratitis, and may be misleading.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba-keratitis] The organism is also capable of invading deeper into the cornea; using metalloproteases it is able to penetrate deep into the stroma of the cornea.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba-keratitis] As the disease progresses, it may penetrate through the cornea but very rarely causes infection inside the eye (endophthalmitis) due to a robust neutrophil response in the anterior chamber.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba-keratitis] While the vast majority of cases of *Acanthamoeba* keratitis occur in contact lens wearers, there have been many cases of *Acanthamoeba* described in those who do not wear contact lenses, especially outside the United States.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba-keratitis] In non-contact lens users, the greatest risks for developing *Acanthamoeba* infection are trauma and exposure to contaminated water.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba-keratitis] Further predisposing factors include contaminated home water supply, and low socioeconomic status.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba-keratitis] Infection is also more commonly seen in tropical or sub-tropical climates.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba-keratitis] Beyond the route of inoculation into the eye and external risk factors, host factors are also likely to play a significant role in the development of *Acanthamoeba* keratitis.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba-keratitis] In fact, studies of contact lens users in the United Kingdom, Japan, and New Zealand found that 400 to 800 per 10,000 asymptomatic contact lens users had lens storage cases contaminated with *Acanthamoeba* spp.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba-keratitis] However, the rate of *Acanthamoeba* keratitis among these patients was only 0.01 to 1.49 per 10,000 contact lens users.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba-keratitis] Although the exact host factors have not been fully described, it is likely that corneal epithelial defects, tear film composition, eye surface pH, and the level of anti-*Acanthamoeba* IgA antibodies in the tear film play a role in the development of *Acanthamoeba* keratitis.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba-keratitis] Species within the genus, *Acanthamoeba*, are generally free-living trophozoites.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba-keratitis] These trophozoites are relatively ubiquitous and can live in, but are not restricted to, tap water, freshwater lakes, rivers and soil.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba-keratitis] In addition to the trophozoite stage, the organism can also form a double-walled cyst which may also be present in the environment, and can be very difficult to eradicate through medical treatment.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba-keratitis] Both of these stages are usually non-nucleated and reproduce by the means of binary fission.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba-keratitis] Due to the relative rarity of *Acanthamoeba* keratitis (AK) compared to other causes of keratitis (bacterial, viral, etc.), it is often misdiagnosed, especially in the early stages of the disease.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba-keratitis] AK should be considered in all patients who use contact lenses, and following corneal abrasions or trauma.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba-keratitis] A thorough history should be obtained, especially relating to contact lens use and any recent changes in contact lens solution, exposure of the eyes to water or foreign objects, and symptoms that the patient is experiencing.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba-keratitis] The symptoms classically attributed to AK include decreased or blurred vision, sensitivity to light (photophobia), redness of the eye (conjunctival hyperemia), and pain out of proportion to physical exam findings.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba-keratitis] Another clinical feature that can distinguish *Acanthamoeba* from bacterial causes of keratitis is a lack of discharge from the eye.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba-keratitis] On physical exam, findings will depend on the stage of the disease.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba-keratitis] Early manifestations in the cornea can be seen as punctate keratopathy, pseudodendrites, and epithelial or subepithelial corneal deposits.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba-keratitis] These features can lead an examiner to confuse AK with a viral keratitis, such as that caused by varicella zoster virus or herpes simplex virus.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba-keratitis] As the disease progresses and infiltrates the corneal stroma, a classic "ring infiltrate" may be present on examination (although this is only seen in about 50% of cases).
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba-keratitis] Corneal ulceration, or in severe cases, perforation, can also occur and may be accompanied by hypopyon.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba-keratitis] In cases of keratitis, diagnosis is typically achieved through evaluation of corneal scrapings.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba-keratitis] Scrapings are taking from the cornea, and plated on agar for culture, and also can be stained using Gram stain and Giemsa stain to differentiate between bacterial keratitis and AK.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba-keratitis] To culture *Acanthamoeba,* scrapings are placed on a non-nutrient agar saline plate seeded with a gram-negative bacteria such as *E. coli*.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba-keratitis] If *Acanthamoeba* are present, they will reproduce readily and become visible on the plate under 10–20 times objective on an inverted microscope.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba-keratitis] Polymerase chain reaction (PCR) can be used to confirm a diagnosis of *Acanthamoeba* keratitis, especially when contact lenses are not involved.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba-keratitis] Confocal microscopy is a non-invasive technique that allows visualization of *Acanthamoeba in vivo* in cases in which corneal scraping, culture, and cytology do not yield a diagnosis.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba-keratitis] Once *Acanthamoeba* keratitis is diagnosed, initiation of timely and appropriate treatment will have a significant impact on visual outcomes.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba-keratitis] Medical therapy aims to eradicate both trophozoite and cystic forms of *Acanthamoeba* and also control the inflammatory response.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba-keratitis] Multiple classes of drugs have been found to be effective in killing the trophozoite form of *Acanthamoeba*, including anti-bacterial, anti-fungal, anti-protozoal, and anti-neoplastic agents.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba-keratitis] However, no single therapy has been found to eliminate both trophozoite and cystic forms, and to eradicate corneal infection.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba-keratitis] One class of medications used in treatment is the biguanides, which include polyhexamethylene biguanide (PHMB) 0.02% to 0.06% drops, and chlorhexidine 0.02 to 0.2% drops.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba-keratitis] These medications disrupt the cell wall of the trophozoite organism, leading to its death.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba-keratitis] However, these agents have shown limited efficacy against the cystic forms.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba-keratitis] Due to the efficacy of these drugs against the *Acanthamoeba,* as well as their low toxicity to the cornea, they are commonly used as the first line medications in the treatment of AK.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba-keratitis] Biguanides have also been found to act synergistically when used in combination with diamidines, with propamidine isethionate and hexamidine being the most commonly used.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba-keratitis] A limitation of diamidine use is relative corneal toxicity with long term use.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba-keratitis] A combined regimen of propamidine, miconazole nitrate, and neomycin has also been suggested.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba-keratitis] Due to the potential for negative longterm visual outcomes with AK, therapy is usually started with a combination of a biguanide and a diamidine.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba-keratitis] Early use of high dose dual therapy helps to eliminate both trophozoite and cyst forms of the organism, while also preventing deep penetration of cysts into the corneal stroma.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba-keratitis] Cysts that are not eradicated from the cornea will cause recurrence.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba-keratitis] The treatment is often initiated by instilling drops onto the surface of the eye every hour, 24 hours a day, for at least the first 48–72 hours.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba-keratitis] If an appropriate response to therapy, this may be reduced to hourly administrations during the day only, which is continued for several weeks to months.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba-keratitis] Beyond anti-amoebic therapies, there is also a role for topical steroids of anti-inflammatory medications in the treatment of *Acanthamoeba* keratitis.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba-keratitis] During infection, severe inflammation in the cornea and anterior chamber can cause more severe symptoms including pain and visual disturbance.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba-keratitis] Topical steroids may be used to reduce this inflammation and thereby alleviate symptoms.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba-keratitis] However, the role of steroids is typically very limited, because their dampening of the immune response may lead to worsening of the infection.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba-keratitis] Additionally, steroids can increase the number of trophozoites in the cornea by inducing excystation.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba-keratitis] Therefore it is typically recommended that steroids be used briefly to aid in symptom resolution, and that anti-amoebic agents be used both during, and for several weeks after topical steroid use.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba-keratitis] Surgical debridement of an infected cornea can also be used to reduce organism load and excise devitalized tissue from the cornea.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba-keratitis] It may also improve the efficacy of medical therapy by promoting penetration of medication into deeper layers of the cornea.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba-keratitis] In cases of corneal ulceration or perforation, or if corneal scarring is severe, corneal transplant may be required.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba-keratitis] This typically involves full thickness transplantation of the cornea from a healthy donor eye.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba-keratitis] The size of the graft should be kept as small as possible, as larger grafts carry a great risk of host rejection, and due to the possibility of graft revision surgery.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba-keratitis] While surgery is capable of restoring vision by replacing a damaged cornea, it also carries risks of recurrent *Acanthamoeba* infection or graft failure.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba-keratitis] For this reason, anti-amoebic medications should be started prior to surgery, and continued for several weeks afterward.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba-keratitis] If there is suspicion or evidence of recurrent infection, cultures should be sent.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba-keratitis] If cultures are positive, anti-amoebic therapy should be continued for 6 months.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba-keratitis] Outcomes following surgery are typically much better for patients who receive surgery for vision improvement following infection resolution, and therefore all efforts should be made to maximize medical management before attempting surgery.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba-keratitis] A study in Austria reported a total of 154 cases of *Acanthamoeba* keratitis over a 20-year period.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba-keratitis] The age of those with AK ranged from 8 to 82 years old and 58% of the people were female.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba-keratitis] The data showed that 89% of the infected patients were contact lens wearers, almost all cases occurred only in one eye, and 19% required a corneal transplant.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba-keratitis] A study in 2023 calculated the incidence of acanthamoeba keratitis to be approximately 2.9 cases per million people.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba] Diseases caused by *Acanthamoeba* include keratitis and granulomatous amoebic encephalitis (GAE).
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba] The latter is often but not always seen in immunosuppressed patients.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba] GAE is caused by the amoebae entering the body through an open wound and then spreading to the brain.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba] The combination of host immune responses and secreted amoebal proteases causes massive brain swelling resulting in death in about 95% of those infected.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba] Granulomatous amoebic encephalitis (GAE) is caused by amoebic infection of the central nervous system (CNS).
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba] It is characterized by neurological symptoms including headache, seizures, and mental-status abnormalities.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba] These worsen progressively over weeks to months, leading to death in most patients.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba] Infection is generally associated with underlying conditions such as immunodeficiency, diabetes, malignancies, malnutrition, systemic lupus erythematosus, and alcoholism.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba] The parasite enters the body through cuts in the skin or by being inhaled into the upper respiratory tract.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba] The parasite then spreads through the blood into the CNS.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba] *Acanthamoeba* crosses the blood–brain barrier by means that are not yet understood.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba] Subsequent invasion of the connective tissue and induction of pro-inflammatory responses leads to neuronal damage that can be fatal within days.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba] Pure granulomatous lesions are rare in patients with AIDS and other related immunodeficiency states, as the patients do not have adequate numbers of CD+ve T-cells to mount a granulomatous response to *Acanthamoeba* infection in CNS and other organs and tissues.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba] A perivascular cuffing with amoebae in necrotic tissue is usual finding in the AIDS and related T-cell immunodeficiency conditions.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba] Brain biopsy normally reveals severe oedema and hemorrhagic necrosis.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba] A patient who has contracted this illness usually displays subacute symptoms, including altered mental status, headaches, fever, neck stiffness, seizures, and focal neurological signs (such as cranial nerve palsies and coma), all leading to death within one week to several months.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba] Due to the rarity of this parasite and a lack of knowledge, no good diagnoses or treatments for *Acanthamoeba* infection are now known.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba] *Acanthamoeba* keratitis cases in the past have resolved from a therapy consisting of atropine and some other drugs with no antimicrobial effects.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba] Recent publications show atropine to interfere with the protist's CHRM1 receptor, causing cell death.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba] Infection usually mimics that of bacterial leptomeningitis, tuberculous meningitis, or viral encephalitis.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba] The misdiagnosis often leads to erroneous, ineffective treatment.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba] In the case that the *Acanthamoeba* is diagnosed correctly, the current treatments, such as amphotericin B, rifampicin, trimethoprim-sulfamethoxazole, ketoconazole, fluconazole, sulfadiazine, or albendazole, are only tentatively successful.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba] Correct and timely diagnosis, as well as improved treatment methods and an understanding of the parasite, are important factors in improving the outcome of infection by *Acanthamoeba*.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba] A paper published in 2013 has shown substantial effects of some FDA-approved drugs with an *in vitro* kill rate above 90%.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba] These results were *in vitro* effects, but as the drugs are already approved, human infections can be targeted after dose calculations in clinical trials done with these diverse groups of drugs.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba] When present in the eye, *Acanthamoeba* strains can cause acanthamoebic keratitis, which may lead to corneal ulcers or even blindness.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba] This condition occurs most often among contact lens wearers who do not properly disinfect their lenses, exacerbated by a failure to wash hands prior to handling the lenses.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba] Multipurpose contact lens solutions are largely ineffective against *Acanthamoeba*, whereas hydrogen peroxide-based solutions have good disinfection characteristics.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba] The first cure of a corneal infection was achieved in 1985 at Moorfields Eye Hospital.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba] In May 2007, Advanced Medical Optics, manufacturer of Complete Moisture Plus Contact Lens Solution products, issued a voluntary recall of their Complete Moisture Plus solutions.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba] The fear was that contact lens wearers who used their solution were at higher risk of acanthamoebic keratitis than contact lens wearers who used other solutions.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba] The manufacturer recalled the product after the Centers for Disease Control in the United States found that 21 people had possibly received an *Acanthamoeba* infection after using Complete Moisture Plus in the month prior to diagnosis.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba] Several species of bacteria that can cause human disease are also able to infect and replicate within *Acanthamoeba* species.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba] These include *Legionella pneumophila*, *Pseudomonas aeruginosa*, and some strains of *Escherichia coli* and *Staphylococcus aureus*.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba] For some of these bacteria, replication inside *Acanthamoeba* has been associated with enhanced growth in macrophages, and increased resistance to some antibiotics.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba] Furthermore, due to the high prevalence of *Acanthamoeba* in the environment, these amoebae have been proposed to serve as an environmental reservoir for some human pathogens.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba] This species is able to lyse bacteria and produce a wide range of enzymes, such as cellulases or chitinases, and probably contributes to the breakdown of organic matter in soil, contributing to the microbial loop.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba] In addition, *Acanthamoeba* has been used extensively to understand the molecular biology of cell motility and cancer cell dormancy by in-depth exploration of the process of encystation.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba] The recently available *Acanthamoeba* genome sequence revealed several orthologs of genes employed in meiosis of sexual eukaryotes.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba] This finding suggests that *Acanthamoeba* is capable of some form of meiosis and may be able to undergo sexual reproduction.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba] Owing to its ease and economy of cultivation, the Neff strain of *A. castellanii*, discovered in a pond in Golden Gate Park in the 1960s, has been effectively used as a classic model organism in the field of cell biology.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba] From just 30 L of simple medium inoculated with *A. castellanii*, about 1 kg of cells can be obtained after several days of aerated culture at room temperature.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba] Pioneered in the laboratory of Edward D.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba] Korn at the National Institutes of Health (NIH), many important biological molecules have been discovered and their pathways elucidated using the *Acanthamoeba* model.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba] *Acanthamoeba* also has served as a model to study the evolution of certain G-proteins.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba] This unicellular eukaryote expresses few GPCRs over its cell membrane that serve vital role for the microorganism, structural homology bioinformatics tools have been used to show the presence of a homolog of human M1-muscarinic receptor in *A. castellanii*.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba] Blocking these muscarinic receptors in past studies has proven to be amoebicidal in Acanthamoeba spp.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba] More recently, voltage-gated calcium channels in *Acanthamoeba* spp.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba] (CavAc) have been reported to have similarities with human voltage-gated calcium channels such as TPC-1 and L-type calcium channels and respond to Ca-channel blockers such as loperamide.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba] This model microbe has been studied to understand complex neurodegenerative states including Alzheimer's disease.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba] Scientists have isolated a neurotransmitter acetylcholine in *Acanthamoeba* and the enzymatic machinery needed for its synthesis.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba] The giant viruses *Mimivirus, Megavirus*, and *Pandoravirus* infect *Acanthamoeba*.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba] Members of the genus *Acanthamoeba* are unusual in serving as hosts for a variety of giant viruses (that have more than 1000 protein-coding genes; for instance, *Pandoravirus*, which has about 2500 protein-coding genes in its genome).
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba] Below is a list of described species of *Acanthamoeba*, with sequence types noted where known.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba] Species that have been identified in diseased patients are marked with *.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba] From the Greek ἄκανθα *akantha* (spike/thorn), which was added before "amoeba" (change) to describe this organism as having a spine-like structure (**acanthopodia**).
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoeba] This organism is now well known as **Acanthamoeba**, an amphizoic, opportunistic, and nonopportunistic protozoan protist widely distributed in the environment.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoebidae] It gets its name from *Acanthamoeba*, its best-known member.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoebidae] However, it also includes other species, such as *Comandonia operculata* and *Protacanthamoeba bohemica*.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoebidae] Many kinds of Acanthamoebidae are highly prevalent in the soil and water of a variety of environments.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoebidae] They are similar to Hartmannella, but have differently structured pseudopodia, in regard to the actin microfilaments that comprise them.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoebidae] Its most prominent member, *Acanthamoeba*, can be potentially pathogenic to humans and animals.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoebidae] It has been described as having a common origin with the Entamoebidae and Dictyosteliida.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoebidae] Members of Acanthamoebidae have a specific form of pseudopodia, dubbed acanthopodia.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoebidae] These acanthopodia are continuously formed and reabsorbed, protrude from every area of the cell's surface, and are usually, short and fine.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoebidae] An exception would be *A. astronyxis* and *A. comandoni*, in which the acanthopodia may be quite long.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoebidae] Sawyer and Griffin point out "[b]undles of actin microfilaments extend as rigid cores into acanthopodia".
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoebidae] They are constantly formed and reabsorbed to induce locomotion, during which time the cell is typically triangular or cone-shaped.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoebidae] The advancing acanthopodia are "wide and tongue-shaped, with irregular margins and filopodia." Sawyer and Griffin also note that the many acanthopodia contain axial bundles of the actin microfilaments, resulting in the irregular shape of the pseudopodia.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoebidae] In regards to the typical physical size of the family Acanthamoebidae, they rarely grow larger than 65 μm or are smaller than 30 μm.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoebidae] The family Acanthamoebidae belongs to the order Centramoebida in the class Discosea, phylum Amoebozoa.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoebidae] Members of Acanthamoebidae are highly prevalent in a variety of environments.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoebidae] In Osaka Prefecture, Japan, members (as well as Naegleria) were found in 68.7% of tapwater samples taken, despite purification.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoebidae] Acanthamoebidae were also found in the St.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthamoebidae] Martin River near Ocean City, Maryland, and are very common in the surface waters of many oceans.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthocephala] The Acanthocephala were long thought to be a discrete phylum.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthocephala] Recent genome analysis has shown that they are descended from, and should be considered as, highly modified rotifers.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthocephala] This unified taxon is sometimes known as Syndermata, or simply as Rotifera, with the acanthocephalans described as a subclass of a rotifer class Hemirotatoria.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthocephala] The earliest recognisable description of Acanthocephala – a worm with a proboscis armed with hooks – was made by Italian author Francesco Redi (1684).
[src:amoebozoa/acanthocephala] In 1771, Joseph Koelreuter proposed the name Acanthocephala.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthocephala] Philipp Ludwig Statius Müller independently called them *Echinorhynchus* in 1776.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthocephala] Karl Rudolphi in 1809 formally named them Acanthocephala.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthocephala] The oldest known member of the group is the Middle Jurassic (living approximately 165 million years ago) taxon *Juracanthocephalus daohugouensis* known from the Jiulongshan Formation (China).
[src:amoebozoa/acanthocephala] The fossil record of the group also includes eggs found in a coprolite from the Late Cretaceous Bauru Group of Brazil, around 70–80 million years old, likely from a crocodyliform.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthocephala] The group may have originated substantially earlier.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthocephala] Acanthocephalans are highly adapted to a parasitic mode of life, and have lost many organs and structures through evolutionary processes.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthocephala] This makes determining relationships with other higher taxa through morphological comparison problematic.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthocephala] A 2016 phylogenetic analysis of the gene order in the mitochondria suggests that Seisonidea and Acanthocephala are sister clades and that the Eurotatoria are the sister clade to this group, producing the cladogram below.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthocephala] Several morphological characteristics distinguish acanthocephalans from other phyla of parasitic worms.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthocephala] Acanthocephalans lack a mouth or alimentary canal.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthocephala] This is a feature they share with the cestoda (tapeworms), although the two groups are not closely related.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthocephala] Adult stages live in the intestines of their host and uptake nutrients which have been digested by the host, directly, through their body surface.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthocephala] The acanthocephalans lack an excretory system, although some species have been shown to possess flame cells (protonephridia).
[src:amoebozoa/acanthocephala] The most notable feature of the acanthocephala is the presence of an anterior, protrudable proboscis that is usually covered with spiny hooks (hence the common name: thorny or spiny headed worm).
[src:amoebozoa/acanthocephala] The proboscis bears rings of recurved hooks arranged in horizontal rows, and it is by means of these hooks that the animal attaches itself to the tissues of its host.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthocephala] The hooks may be of two or three shapes, usually: longer, more slender hooks are arranged along the length of the proboscis, with several rows of more sturdy, shorter nasal hooks around the base of the proboscis.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthocephala] The proboscis is used to pierce the gut wall of the final host, and hold the parasite fast while it completes its life cycle.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthocephala] Like the body, the proboscis is hollow, and its cavity is separated from the body cavity by a *septum* or *proboscis sheath*.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthocephala] Traversing the cavity of the proboscis are muscle-strands inserted into the tip of the proboscis at one end and into the septum at the other.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthocephala] Their contraction causes the proboscis to be invaginated into its cavity.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthocephala] The whole proboscis apparatus can also be, at least partially, withdrawn into the body cavity, and this is effected by two retractor muscles which run from the posterior aspect of the septum to the body wall.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthocephala] Some of the acanthocephalans (perforating acanthocephalans) can insert their proboscis in the intestine of the host and open the way to the abdominal cavity.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthocephala] The size of these animals varies greatly, ranging from a few millimetres in length to *Macracanthorhynchus hirudinaceus*, which measures from 10 to 65 centimetres (3.9 to 25.6 in).
[src:amoebozoa/acanthocephala] A curious feature shared by both larva and adult is the large size of many of the cells, e.g. the nerve cells and cells forming the uterine bell.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthocephala] Polyploidy is common, with up to 343n having been recorded in some species.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthocephala] The body surface of the acanthocephala is peculiar.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthocephala] Externally, the skin has a thin tegument that covers the epidermis and consists of a syncytium with no cell walls.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthocephala] The syncytium is traversed by a series of branching tubules containing fluid and is controlled by a few wandering, amoeboid nuclei.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthocephala] Inside the syncytium is an irregular layer of circular muscle fibres, and within this again some rather scattered longitudinal fibres; there is no endothelium.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthocephala] In their micro-structure the muscular fibres resemble those of nematodes.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthocephala] Except for the absence of the longitudinal fibres the skin of the proboscis resembles that of the body, but the fluid-containing tubules of the proboscis are shut off from those of the body.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthocephala] The canals of the proboscis open into a circular vessel which runs round its base.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthocephala] From the circular canal two sac-like projections called the *lemnisci* run into the cavity of the body, alongside the proboscis cavity.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthocephala] Each consists of a prolongation of the syncytial material of the proboscis skin, penetrated by canals and sheathed with a muscular coat.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthocephala] They seem to act as reservoirs into which the fluid which is used to keep the proboscis "erect" can withdraw when it is retracted, and from which the fluid can be driven out when it is wished to expand the proboscis.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthocephala] The central ganglion of the nervous system lies behind the proboscis sheath or septum.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthocephala] It innervates the proboscis and projects two stout trunks posteriorly which supply the body.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthocephala] Each of these trunks is surrounded by muscles, and this nerve-muscle complex is called a *retinaculum*.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthocephala] In the male at least there is also a genital ganglion.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthocephala] Some scattered papillae may possibly be sense-organs.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthocephala] Acanthocephalans have complex life cycles, involving a number of hosts, for both developmental and resting stages.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthocephala] Complete life cycles have been worked out for only 25 species.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthocephala] The Acanthocephala are dioecious (an individual organism is either male or female).
[src:amoebozoa/acanthocephala] There is a structure called the *genital ligament* which runs from the posterior end of the proboscis sheath to the posterior end of the body.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthocephala] In the male, two testes lie on either side of this.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthocephala] Each opens in a vas deferens which bears three diverticula or *vesiculae seminales*.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthocephala] The male also possesses three pairs of cement glands, found behind the testes, which pour their secretions through a duct into the vasa deferentia.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthocephala] These unite and end in a penis which opens posteriorly.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthocephala] In the female, the ovaries are found, like the testes, as rounded bodies along the ligament.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthocephala] From the ovaries, masses of ova dehisce into the body cavity, floating in its fluids for fertilization by male's sperm.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthocephala] After fertilization, each egg contains a developing embryo.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthocephala] (These embryos hatch into first stage larva.) The fertilized eggs are brought into the uterus by actions of the *uterine bell*, a funnel like opening continuous with the uterus.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthocephala] At the junction of the bell and the uterus there is a second, smaller opening situated dorsally.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthocephala] The bell "swallows" the matured eggs and passes them on into the uterus.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthocephala] (Immature embryos are passed back into the body cavity through the dorsal opening.) From the uterus, mature eggs leave the female's body via her oviduct, pass into the host's alimentary canal and are expelled from the host's body within feces.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthocephala] Having been expelled by the female, the acanthocephalan egg is released along with the feces of the host.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthocephala] For development to occur, the egg, containing the acanthor, needs to be ingested by an arthropod, usually a crustacean (there is one known life cycle which uses a mollusc as a first intermediate host).
[src:amoebozoa/acanthocephala] Inside the intermediate host, the acanthor is released from the egg and develops into an acanthella.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthocephala] It then penetrates the gut wall, moves into the body cavity, encysts, and begins transformation into the infective cystacanth stage.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthocephala] This form has all the organs of the adult save the reproductive ones.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthocephala] The parasite is released when the first intermediate host is ingested.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthocephala] This can be by a suitable final host, in which case the cystacanth develops into a mature adult, or by a paratenic host, in which the parasite again forms a cyst.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthocephala] When consumed by a suitable final host, the cycstacant *excysts*, everts its proboscis and pierces the gut wall.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthocephala] It then feeds, grows and develops its sexual organs.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthocephala] The male uses the excretions of its *cement glands* to plug the vagina of the female, preventing subsequent matings from occurring.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthocephala] Embryos develop inside the female, and the life cycle repeats.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthocephala] Thorny-headed worms begin their life cycle inside invertebrates that reside in marine or freshwater systems.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthocephala] One example is *Polymorphus paradoxus.* *Gammarus lacustris*, a small crustacean that inhabits ponds and rivers, is one invertebrate that *P. paradoxus* may occupy; ducks are one of the definitive hosts.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthocephala] This crustacean is preyed on by ducks and hides by avoiding light and staying away from the surface.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthocephala] However, infection by *P. paradoxus* changes its behavior and appearance in a number of ways that increase its chance of being eaten.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthocephala] First, infection significantly reduces *G. lacustris'*s photophobia; as a result, it becomes attracted toward light and swims to the surface.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthocephala] Second, an infected organism will even go so far as to find a rock or a plant on the surface, clamp its mouth down, and latch on, making it easy prey for the duck.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthocephala] Finally, infection reduces the pigment distribution and amount in *G. lacustris,* causing the host to turn blue; unlike their normal brown colour, this makes the crustacean stand out and increases the chance the duck will see it.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthocephala] Experiments have shown that altered serotonin levels are likely responsible for at least some of these changes in behaviour.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthocephala] One experiment found that serotonin induces clinging behavior in *G. lacustris* similar to that seen in infected organisms.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthocephala] Another showed that infected *G. lacustris* had approximately 3 times as many serotonin-producing sites in its ventral nerve cord.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthocephala] Acanthocephalosis, a disease caused by *Acanthacephalus* infection, is prevalent in aquaculture, occurring in Atlantic salmon, rainbow and brown trout, tilapia, and tambaqui.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthocephala] Increasing occurrence in Brazilian farming of tambaqui has been reported, and in 2003 *Acanthacephalus* was first reported in cultured red snapper in Taiwan.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthocephala] The life cycle of *Polymorphus* spp. normally occurs between sea ducks (e.g. eiders and scoters) and small crabs.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthocephala] Infections found in commercial-sized lobsters in Canada were probably acquired from crabs that form an important dietary item of lobsters.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthocephala] Cystacanths occurring in lobsters can cause economic loss to fishermen.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthocephala] There are no known methods of prevention or control.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthocephala] Although they rarely infect humans, worms in the phylum Acanthocephala cause the disease acanthocephaliasis in humans.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthocephala] The earliest known infection was found in a prehistoric man in Utah.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthocephala] This infection was dated to 1869 ± 160 BC.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthocephala] The species involved was thought to be *Moniliformis clarki* which is still common in the area.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthocephala] The first report of an isolate in historic times was by Lambl in 1859 when he isolated *Macracanthorhynchus hirudinaceus* from a child in Prague.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthocephala] Lindemann in 1865 reported that this organism was commonly isolated in Russia.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthocephala] The reason for this was discovered by Schneider in 1871 when he found that an intermediate host, the scarabaeid beetle grub, was commonly eaten raw.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthocephala] The first report of clinical symptoms was by Calandruccio who in 1888 while in Italy infected himself by ingesting larvae.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthocephala] He reported gastrointestinal disturbances and shed eggs in two weeks.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthocephala] Subsequent natural infections have since been reported.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthocephala] Eight species have been isolated from humans to date.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthocephala] *Moniliformis moniliformis* is the most common isolate.
[src:amoebozoa/acanthocephala] Other isolates include *Acanthocephalus bufonis* and *Corynosoma strumosum*.
[src:amoebozoa/acidobacteriota] Members of this phylum are physiologically diverse, and can be found in a variety of environments including soil, decomposing wood, hot springs, oceans, caves, and metal-contaminated soils.
[src:amoebozoa/acidobacteriota] The members of this phylum are particularly abundant in soil habitats representing up to 52% of the total bacterial community.
[src:amoebozoa/acidobacteriota] Environmental factors such as pH and nutrients have been seen to drive Acidobacteriota dynamics.
[src:amoebozoa/acidobacteriota] Many Acidobacteriota are acidophilic, including the first described member of the phylum, *Acidobacterium capsulatum*.
[src:amoebozoa/acidobacteriota] There is much that is unknown about Acidobacteria both in their form and function.
[src:amoebozoa/acidobacteriota] Thus, this is a growing field of microbiology.
[src:amoebozoa/acidobacteriota] Some of this uncertainty can be attributed to the difficulty with which these bacteria are grown in the laboratory.
[src:amoebozoa/acidobacteriota] There has been recent success in propagation by using low concentrations of nutrients in combination with high amounts of CO2, yet, progress is still quite slow.
[src:amoebozoa/acidobacteriota] These new methods have only allowed approximately 30% of subdivisions to have species documented.
[src:amoebozoa/acidobacteriota] Additionally, many of the samples sequenced do not have taxonomic names as they have not yet been fully characterized.
[src:amoebozoa/acidobacteriota] This area of study is a very current topic, and scientific understanding is expected to grow and change as new information comes to light.
[src:amoebozoa/acidobacteriota] Other notable species are *Holophaga foetida*, *Geothrix fermentans*, *Acanthopleuribacter pedis* and *Bryobacter aggregatus*.
[src:amoebozoa/acidobacteriota] Since they have only recently been discovered and the large majority have not been cultured, the ecology and metabolism of these bacteria is not well understood.
[src:amoebozoa/acidobacteriota] However, these bacteria may be an important contributor to ecosystems, since they are particularly abundant within soils.
[src:amoebozoa/acidobacteriota] Members of subdivisions 1, 4, and 6 are found to be particularly abundant in soils.
[src:amoebozoa/acidobacteriota] As well as their natural soil habitat, unclassified subdivision 2 Acidobacteriota have also been identified as a contaminant of DNA extraction kit reagents, which may lead to their erroneous appearance in microbiota or metagenomic datasets.
[src:amoebozoa/acidobacteriota] Members of subdivision 1 have been found to dominate in low pH conditions.
[src:amoebozoa/acidobacteriota] Additionally, Acidobacteriota from acid mine drainage have been found to be more adapted to acidic pH conditions (pH 2–3) compared to Acidobacteriota from soils, potentially due to cell specialization and enzyme stability.
[src:amoebozoa/acidobacteriota] The G+C content of Acidobacteria genomes are consistent within their subdivisions - above 60% for group V fragments and roughly 10% lower for group III fragments.
[src:amoebozoa/acidobacteriota] The majority of Acidobacteriota are considered aerobes.
[src:amoebozoa/acidobacteriota] There are some Acidobacteriota that are considered anaerobes within subdivision 8 and subdivision 23.
[src:amoebozoa/acidobacteriota] It has been found that some strains of Acidobacteriota originating from soils have the genomic potential to respire oxygen at atmospheric and sub-atmospheric concentrations.
[src:amoebozoa/acidobacteriota] Members of the *Acidobacteriota* phylum have been considered oligotrophic bacteria due to high abundances in low organic carbon environments.
[src:amoebozoa/acidobacteriota] However, the variation in this phylum may indicate that they may not have the same ecological strategy.
[src:amoebozoa/acidobacteriota] The first species, *Acidobacterium capsulatum*, of this phylum was discovered in 1991.
[src:amoebozoa/acidobacteriota] However, Acidobacteriota were not recognized as a distinct clade until 1997, and were not recognized as a phylum until 2012.
[src:amoebozoa/acidobacteriota] In an effort to further classify Acidobacteria, 16S rRNA gene regions were sequenced from many different strains.
[src:amoebozoa/acidobacteriota] These sequences lead to the formation of subdivisions within the phyla.
[src:amoebozoa/acidobacteriota] Today, there are 26 accepted subdivisions recognized in the Ribosomal Database Project.
[src:amoebozoa/acidobacteriota] Much of this variety comes from populations of acidobacteria found in soils contaminated with uranium.
[src:amoebozoa/acidobacteriota] Therefore, most of the known species in this phyla are concentrated in a few of the subdivisions, the largest being #1.
[src:amoebozoa/acidobacteriota] Most of these microbes are aerobes, and they are all heterotrophic.
[src:amoebozoa/acidobacteriota] Subdivision 1 contains 11 of the known genera in addition to the majority of the species that have been able to be cultivated thus far.
[src:amoebozoa/acidobacteriota] Within the 22 known genera, there are 40 conclusive species.
[src:amoebozoa/acidobacteriota] The genera are divided amongst subdivisions 3, 4, 8, 10, 23, and 1.
[src:amoebozoa/acidobacteriota] As the Acidobateria are a developing area of microbiology, it is hypothesized that these numbers will change drastically with further study.
[src:amoebozoa/acidobacteriota] Some members of subdivision 1 are able to use D-glucose, D-xylose, and lactose as carbon sources, but are unable to use fucose or sorbose.
[src:amoebozoa/acidobacteriota] Members of subdivision 1 also contain enzymes such as galactosidases used in the breakdown of sugars.
[src:amoebozoa/acidobacteriota] Members of subdivision 4 have been found to use chitin as a carbon source.
[src:amoebozoa/acidobacteriota] Despite the presence of genetic information generally known to encode for carbohydrate processing machinery in various genera of Acidobacteria, several experimental studies have demonstrated the inability to break down various polysaccharides.
[src:amoebozoa/acidobacteriota] Cellulose is the main component of plant cell walls and a seemingly opportune resource for carbon.
[src:amoebozoa/acidobacteriota] However, only a single species across all subdivisions has been shown to process it, *Telmactobacter bradus* from subvision 1.
[src:amoebozoa/acidobacteriota] Researchers believe that an additional factor in the lack of understanding of carbon degradation by acidobacteria may stem from the present limited ability to provide adequate cultivation conditions.
[src:amoebozoa/acidobacteriota] To study the natural behavior of these bacteria, they must grow and live in a controlled, observable environment.
[src:amoebozoa/acidobacteriota] If such a habitat cannot be provided, recorded data cannot reliably report on the activity of the microbes in question.
[src:amoebozoa/acidobacteriota] Therefore, the inconsistencies between genome sequence based predictions and observed carbon processes may be explained by present study methods.
[src:amoebozoa/acidobacteriota] There has been no clear evidence that Acidobacteriota are involved in nitrogen-cycle processes such as nitrification, denitrification, or nitrogen fixation.
[src:amoebozoa/acidobacteriota] However, *Geothrix fermantans* was shown to be able to reduce nitrate and contained the norB gene.
[src:amoebozoa/acidobacteriota] The NorB gene was also identified in *Koribacter verstailis* and *Solibacter usitatus*.
[src:amoebozoa/acidobacteriota] In addition, the presence of the nirA gene has been observed in members of subdivision 1.
[src:amoebozoa/acidobacteriota] Additionally, to date, all genomes have been described to directly uptake ammonium via ammonium channel transporter family genes.
[src:amoebozoa/acidobacteriota] Acidobacteriota can use both inorganic and organic nitrogen as their nitrogen sources.
[src:amoebozoa/acidobacteriota] The currently accepted taxonomy is based on the List of Prokaryotic names with Standing in Nomenclature and National Center for Biotechnology Information (NCBI).
[src:amoebozoa/amoebozoa] Some are only 10–20 μm in diameter, while others are among the largest protozoa.
[src:amoebozoa/amoebozoa] The well-known species *Amoeba proteus,* which may reach 800 μm in length, is often studied in schools and laboratories as a representative cell or model organism, partly because of its convenient size.
[src:amoebozoa/amoebozoa] Multinucleate amoebae like *Chaos* and *Pelomyxa* may be several millimetres in length, and some multicellular amoebozoa, such as the "dog vomit" slime mold *Fuligo septica*, can cover an area of several square meters.
[src:amoebozoa/amoebozoa] Amoebozoa is a large and diverse group, but certain features are common to many of its members.
[src:amoebozoa/amoebozoa] The amoebozoan cell is typically divided into a granular central mass, called endoplasm, and a clear outer layer, called ectoplasm.
[src:amoebozoa/amoebozoa] During locomotion, the endoplasm flows forwards and the ectoplasm runs backwards along the outside of the cell.
[src:amoebozoa/amoebozoa] In motion, many amoebozoans have a clearly defined anterior and posterior and may assume a "monopodial" form, with the entire cell functioning as a single pseudopod.
[src:amoebozoa/amoebozoa] Large pseudopods may produce numerous clear projections called subpseudopodia (or determinate pseudopodia), which are extended to a certain length and then retracted, either for the purpose of locomotion or food intake.
[src:amoebozoa/amoebozoa] A cell may also form multiple indeterminate pseudopodia, through which the entire contents of the cell flow in the direction of locomotion.
[src:amoebozoa/amoebozoa] These are more or less tubular and are mostly filled with granular endoplasm.
[src:amoebozoa/amoebozoa] The cell mass flows into a leading pseudopod, and the others ultimately retract, unless the organism changes direction.
[src:amoebozoa/amoebozoa] While most amoebozoans are "naked," like the familiar *Amoeba* and *Chaos*, or covered with a loose coat of minute scales, like *Cochliopodium* and *Korotnevella*, members of the order Arcellinida form rigid shells, or tests, equipped with a single aperture through which the pseudopods emerge.
[src:amoebozoa/amoebozoa] In all amoebozoa, the primary mode of nutrition is phagocytosis, in which the cell surrounds potential food particles with its pseudopods, sealing them into vacuoles within which they may be digested and absorbed.
[src:amoebozoa/amoebozoa] Some amoebozoans have a posterior bulb called a uroid, which may serve to accumulate waste, periodically detaching from the rest of the cell.
[src:amoebozoa/amoebozoa] When food is scarce, most species can form cysts, which may be carried aerially and introduce them to new environments.
[src:amoebozoa/amoebozoa] In slime moulds, these structures are called spores, and form on stalked structures called fruiting bodies or sporangia.
[src:amoebozoa/amoebozoa] Mixotrophic species living in a symbiotic relationship with microalgae of the genus Chlorella, which lives inside the cytoplasm of their host, have been found in Arcellinida and *Mayorella*.
[src:amoebozoa/amoebozoa] The majority of Amoebozoa lack flagella and more generally do not form microtubule-supported structures except during mitosis.
[src:amoebozoa/amoebozoa] However, flagella do occur among the Archamoebae, and many slime moulds produce biflagellate gametes .
[src:amoebozoa/amoebozoa] The flagellum is generally anchored by a cone of microtubules, suggesting a close relationship to the opisthokonts.
[src:amoebozoa/amoebozoa] The mitochondria in amoebozoan cells characteristically have branching tubular cristae.
[src:amoebozoa/amoebozoa] However, among the Archamoebae, which are adapted to anoxic or microaerophilic habitats, mitochondria have been lost.
[src:amoebozoa/amoebozoa] Strong similarities between Amoebozoa and Opisthokonts lead to the hypothesis that they form a distinct clade.
[src:amoebozoa/amoebozoa] In their Revised Classification of Eukaryotes (2012), Adl et al. proposed Amorphea as a more suitable name for a clade of approximately the same composition, a sister group to the Diaphoretickes.
[src:amoebozoa/amoebozoa] More recent work places the members of Amorphea together with the malawimonids and collodictyonids in a proposed clade called Opimoda, which comprises one of two major lineages diverging at the root of the eukaryote tree of life, the other being Diphoda.
[src:amoebozoa/amoebozoa] Traditionally all amoebozoa with lobose pseudopods were grouped together in the class Lobosea, placed with other amoeboids in the phylum Sarcodina or Rhizopoda, but these were considered to be unnatural groups.
[src:amoebozoa/amoebozoa] Structural and genetic studies identified the percolozoans and several archamoebae as independent groups.
[src:amoebozoa/amoebozoa] In phylogenies based on rRNA their representatives were separate from other amoebae, and appeared to diverge near the base of eukaryotic evolution, as did most slime molds.
[src:amoebozoa/amoebozoa] However, revised trees by Cavalier-Smith and Chao in 1996 suggested that the remaining lobosans do form a monophyletic group, to which the Archamoebae and Mycetozoa were closely related, although the percolozoans were not.
[src:amoebozoa/amoebozoa] Subsequently, they emended the phylum Amoebozoa to include both the subphylum Lobosa and a new subphylum Conosa, comprising the Archamoebae and the Mycetozoa.
[src:amoebozoa/amoebozoa] Recent molecular genetic data appear to support this primary division of the Amoebozoa into Lobosa and Conosa.
[src:amoebozoa/amoebozoa] The former, as defined by Cavalier-Smith and his collaborators, consists largely of the classic Lobosea: non-flagellated amoebae with blunt, lobose pseudopods (*Amoeba*, *Acanthamoeba, Arcella, Difflugia etc.*).
[src:amoebozoa/amoebozoa] The latter is made up of both amoeboid and flagellated cells, characteristically with more pointed or slightly branching subpseudopodia (Archamoebae and the Mycetozoan slime molds).
[src:amoebozoa/amoebozoa] From older studies by Cavalier-Smith, Chao & Lewis 2016 and Silar 2016.
[src:amoebozoa/amoebozoa] Also recent phylogeny indicates the Lobosa are paraphyletic: Conosa is sister of the Cutosea.
[src:amoebozoa/amoebozoa] Vase-shaped microfossils (VSMs) discovered around the world show that amoebozoans have existed since the Neoproterozoic Era.
[src:amoebozoa/amoebozoa] The fossil species *Melanocyrillium hexodiadema*, *Palaeoarcella athanata*, and *Hemisphaeriella ornata* come from rocks 750 million years old.
[src:amoebozoa/amoebozoa] All three VSMs share a hemispherical shape, invaginated aperture, and regular indentations, that strongly resemble modern arcellinids, which are shell-bearing amoebozoans belonging to the class Tubulinea.
[src:amoebozoa/amoebozoa] *P. athanata* in particular looks the same as the extant genus *Arcella*.
[src:amoebozoa/amoebozoa] In sexually reproducing eukaryotes, homologous recombination (HR) ordinarily occurs during meiosis.
[src:amoebozoa/amoebozoa] The meiosis-specific recombinase, Dmc1, is required for efficient meiotic HR, and Dmc1 is expressed in *Entamoeba histolytica*.
[src:amoebozoa/amoebozoa] The purified Dmc1 from *E. histolytica* forms presynaptic filaments and catalyzes ATP-dependent homologous DNA pairing and DNA strand exchange over at least several thousand base pairs.
[src:amoebozoa/amoebozoa] The DNA pairing and strand exchange reactions are enhanced by the eukaryotic meiosis-specific recombination accessory factor (heterodimer) Hop2-Mnd1.
[src:amoebozoa/amoebozoa] These processes are central to meiotic recombination, suggesting that *E. histolytica* undergoes meiosis.
[src:amoebozoa/amoebozoa] Studies of *Entamoeba invadens* found that, during the conversion from the tetraploid uninucleate trophozoite to the tetranucleate cyst, homologous recombination is enhanced.
[src:amoebozoa/amoebozoa] Expression of genes with functions related to the major steps of meiotic recombination also increased during encystations.
[src:amoebozoa/amoebozoa] These findings in *E. invadens*, combined with evidence from studies of *E. histolytica* indicate the presence of meiosis in the *Entamoeba*.
[src:amoebozoa/amoebozoa] A comparative genetic analysis indicated that meiotic processes are present in all major amoebozoan lineages.
[src:amoebozoa/amoebozoa] Since *Amoebozoa* diverged early from the eukaryotic family tree, these results also suggest that meiosis was present early in eukaryotic evolution.
[src:amoebozoa/amoebozoa] Amoebiasis, also known as amebiasis or entamoebiasis, is an infection caused by any of the amoebozoans of the *Entamoeba* group.
[src:amoebozoa/amoebozoa] Symptoms are most common upon infection by *Entamoeba histolytica*.
[src:amoebozoa/amoebozoa] Amoebiasis can present with no, mild, or severe symptoms.
[src:amoebozoa/amoebozoa] Symptoms may include abdominal pain, mild diarrhoea, bloody diarrhea or severe colitis with tissue death and perforation.
[src:amoebozoa/amoebozoa] This last complication may cause peritonitis.
[src:amoebozoa/amoebozoa] People affected may develop anemia due to loss of blood.
[src:amoebozoa/amoebozoa] Invasion of the intestinal lining causes amoebic bloody diarrhea or amoebic colitis.
[src:amoebozoa/amoebozoa] If the parasite reaches the bloodstream it can spread through the body, most frequently ending up in the liver where it causes amoebic liver abscesses.
[src:amoebozoa/amoebozoa] Liver abscesses can occur without previous diarrhea.
[src:amoebozoa/amoebozoa] Cysts of *Entamoeba* can survive for up to a month in soil or for up to 45 minutes under fingernails.
[src:amoebozoa/amoebozoa] It is important to differentiate between amoebiasis and bacterial colitis.
[src:amoebozoa/amoebozoa] The preferred diagnostic method is through faecal examination under microscope, but requires a skilled microscopist and may not be reliable when excluding infection.
[src:amoebozoa/amoebozoa] This method however may not be able to separate between specific types.
[src:amoebozoa/amoebozoa] Increased white blood cell count is present in severe cases, but not in mild ones.
[src:amoebozoa/amoebozoa] The most accurate test is for antibodies in the blood, but it may remain positive following treatment.
[src:amoebozoa/amoebozoa] Prevention of amoebiasis is by separating food and water from faeces and by proper sanitation measures.
[src:amoebozoa/amoebozoa] There are two treatment options depending on the location of the infection.
[src:amoebozoa/amoebozoa] Amoebiasis in tissues is treated with either metronidazole, tinidazole, nitazoxanide, dehydroemetine or chloroquine, while luminal infection is treated with diloxanide furoate or iodoquinoline.
[src:amoebozoa/amoebozoa] For treatment to be effective against all stages of the amoeba may require a combination of medications.
[src:amoebozoa/amoebozoa] Infections without symptoms do not require treatment but infected individuals can spread the parasite to others and treatment can be considered.
[src:amoebozoa/amoebozoa] Treatment of other *Entamoeba* infections apart from *E. histolytica* is not needed.
[src:amoebozoa/amoebozoa] Amoebiasis is present all over the world.
[src:amoebozoa/amoebozoa] About 480 million people are infected with what appears to be *E. histolytica* and these result in the death of between 40,000–110,000 people every year.
[src:amoebozoa/amoebozoa] Most infections are now ascribed to *E. dispar*.
[src:amoebozoa/amoebozoa] *E. dispar* is more common in certain areas and symptomatic cases may be fewer than previously reported.
[src:amoebozoa/amoebozoa] The first case of amoebiasis was documented in 1875 and in 1891 the disease was described in detail, resulting in the terms *amoebic dysentery* and *amoebic liver abscess*.
[src:amoebozoa/amoebozoa] Further evidence from the Philippines in 1913 found that upon ingesting cysts of *E. histolytica* volunteers developed the disease.
[src:amoebozoa/amoebozoa] It has been known since 1897 that at least one non-disease-causing species of *Entamoeba* existed (*Entamoeba coli*), but it was first formally recognized by the WHO in 1997 that *E. histolytica* was two species, despite this having first been proposed in 1925.
[src:amoebozoa/amoebozoa] In addition to the now-recognized *E. dispar* evidence shows there are at least two other species of *Entamoeba* that look the same in humans - *E. moshkovskii* and *Entamoeba bangladeshi*.
[src:amoebozoa/amoebozoa] The reason these species haven't been differentiated until recently is because of the reliance on appearance.
